10:["$","$1","c",{"children":[[["$","section",null,{"className":"border-b border-zinc-800 py-16 md:py-20","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6","children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-black tracking-tight text-white sm:text-5xl md:text-6xl","children":["How to Never Be Late to"," ",["$","span",null,{"className":"text-green-500","children":"Meetings Again"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-400","children":"Most people know when their meetings are. They still run late. The problem isn't your calendar — it's the gap between knowing a meeting is coming and actually leaving in time to make it. This page explains why that gap exists and how to close it for good."}]]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6","children":[["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-14","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-2xl font-black tracking-tight text-white sm:text-3xl","children":"Why Calendar Reminders Don't Work"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4 text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Calendar apps send reminders as notifications — a banner that slides in, sits there for a few seconds, and disappears. You might glance at it and think ",["$","em",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300","children":"\"got it, meeting in 30 minutes\""}]," and then keep doing what you were doing. Thirty minutes later, you're still at your desk when you should already be walking out the door."]}],["$","p",null,{"children":["The problem is that reminders are ",["$","strong",null,{"className":"text-white","children":"informative"}],", not"," ",["$","strong",null,{"className":"text-white","children":"imperative"}],". They tell you something is coming. They don't actually interrupt what you're doing or create the urgency to stop and leave. They're easy to dismiss with one tap and just as easy to mentally file away and forget."]}],["$","p",null,{"children":["There's also a timing problem. Most people set reminders for when a meeting ",["$","em",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300","children":"starts"}],", not for when they need to"," ",["$","em",null,{"className":"text-zinc-300","children":"leave"}],". A 2:00 PM meeting reminder at 2:00 PM doesn't help you — you needed to leave at 1:45. By the time the reminder fires, you're already running behind."]}]]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-14","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-2xl font-black tracking-tight text-white sm:text-3xl","children":"What Actually Works: Alarms Before Meetings"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4 text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":"You don't use a calendar reminder to wake up in the morning. You use an alarm — because alarms are loud, persistent, and hard to ignore. The same logic applies to meetings."}],["$","p",null,{"children":["An alarm that fires 20 or 30 minutes before a meeting, timed to when you actually need to start wrapping up and heading out, is fundamentally different from a notification you can swipe away. It creates a clear signal: ",["$","strong",null,{"className":"text-white","children":"stop what you're doing. It's time to go."}]]}],["$","p",null,{"children":["The key shift is planning around ",["$","strong",null,{"className":"text-white","children":"departure time"}],", not meeting start time. Your alarm should fire when you need to leave — accounting for travel, parking, getting settled — not at the moment the meeting begins. Once you make that shift, the constant low-level anxiety of \"wait, when do I need to leave?\" disappears."]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-6 rounded-xl border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-900 p-5 text-sm text-zinc-400","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"font-semibold text-white","children":"The departure-first rule:"}],"$L13"]}]]}],"$L14","$L15"]}],"$L16","$L17","$L18"],null,"$L19"]}]
